Heading to @Space_Station, the #Cygnus spacecraft will deliver ~7,600 pounds of cargo. 1114266006006796288.text:
Creating a Martian explorer

A team installs the #Mars2020 rover’s MOXIE instrument, which will test a way that future astronauts might produce oxygen from the Red Planet’s atmosphere. More: https://go.nasa.gov/2VoxwS1  #Moon2Marspic.twitter.com/GkNZLiuOHx

1120028946500919297.text: Our magnificent planet is ready for its close-up , & on #EarthDay, April 22, we’re calling on YOU! Help us celebrate by uploading a photo of your favorite natural features using #PictureEarth. Learn how your pictures could be featured in future projects: https://go.nasa.gov/2UJGZXM pic.twitter.com/xwlYMqqBqu

1116731768374272001.text: A free flying robot that can help with chores, a study on human aging, and a Bio-Analyzer are just a few of the @ISS_Research experiments launching to the space station! Learn more about what's on board: https://go.nasa.gov/2uYRKpV .https://go.nasa.gov/2uYRKpV

1123249403144413188.text: We've requested @SpaceX move off from May 1 for the launch of their 17th commercial resupply mission to the @Space_Station as teams continue work on the station's power system. The earliest possible launch opportunity is no earlier than May 3. Details: https://go.nasa.gov/2PFenZT pic.twitter.com/cAY0RjWqul

1118614837062279168.text: Time is ticking and we are minutes away from liftoff!  Watch the 4:46pm ET launch of @NorthropGrumman’s #Cygnus cargo spacecraft from @NASA_Wallops in Virginia: https://twitter.com/i/broadcasts/1kvJpODLORQGE …pic.twitter.com/qVkQePg0A5

1121051785358204928.text: Today marks 29 years since Hubble was launched into space aboard the Space Shuttle Discovery! It has been unlocking the mysteries of the universe for nearly three decades. Here are a few science achievements from Hubble’s latest year in orbit. #Hubble29pic.twitter.com/gEC6kScLEV

1120768743284469760.text: Mars, I hear you. I’ve detected some quiet but distinct shaking on #Mars. The faint rumbles appear to have come from the inside of the planet, and are still being studied by my team. Take a listen.http://go.nasa.gov/2GCEBtm pic.twitter.com/Z8Hn03jigO

1121446772423970816.text:
Can you build a running track on Mars? How about grow food on Mars?

Yes—with the help of @Dartmouth's School of Engineering. Their top-notch idea won NASA’s 2019 BIG Idea Challenge. Learn more about their creative concept:https://go.nasa.gov/2L2NrVw

1118606295852933120.text: Today, we’re sending flying robotic helpers to the @Space_Station to assist @NASA_Astronauts with routine tasks and chores in space! Get to know our cube-shaped Astrobee robots  before they leave the planet: https://go.nasa.gov/2VMDIU4 pic.twitter.com/oFJjsf01Y5

1123029704129306625.text: Excited for Wednesday’s SpaceX cargo launch? We don’t blame you! This mission will support dozens of the 250+ science experiments on board the @Space_Station. Hear the latest pre-launch updates Tuesday at 1pm ET: https://go.nasa.gov/2V5N9So pic.twitter.com/JO9E9209Vr

1122682387530440705.text:
Didn't get enough dragons during the #BattleOfWinterfell? Good news: @SpaceX is launching one this week

On Wednesday at 3:59 ET a #dragon capsule will launch aboard a Falcon 9   on its way to the @Space_Station: https://go.nasa.gov/2INpShg pic.twitter.com/cLehLconHw

1119204532586553345.text: After its capture, the @NorthropGrumman #Cygnus spacecraft was bolted into place on the @Space_Station’s Earth-facing port of the Unity module at 7:31am ET. It will remain at the station until July 23. Details: https://go.nasa.gov/2Gr67ZD pic.twitter.com/IP55VO5QcP

1118615027517407238.text: Our small robots taking on big jobs are heading to the @Space_Station via @northropgrumman's #Cygnus spacecraft. Free-flying Astrobee can help scientists and engineers test technologies for use in microgravity, pitch in with astronauts' chores, and more: https://go.nasa.gov/2V3foAn pic.twitter.com/GAPFuBUcgx

1120419076491370499.text: Every day is #EarthDay for Christy Hansen at @NASAGoddard, who works with scientists and engineers to put instrumentation on NASA airplanes for the study of Earth from remote locations.  To learn more about our Airborne Science Program, visit: https://airbornescience.nasa.gov/ pic.twitter.com/uUVFaAo647

1118615336264392706.text: Another technology heading to space via the @northropgrumman #Cygnus spacecraft is a biology experiment to test in-space nutrient production critical to astronauts' health for long-duration missions to the Moon and beyond. Learn more about BioNutrients: https://www.nasa.gov/ames/bionutrients …pic.twitter.com/BWxpjwvEy2
